<P>
RAINBOW WARRIORS HOPE FOR LOW SCORE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT MILLER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hawaii Coach Bob Wagner figures he knows what it will take to beat the Aztecs 
Saturday at San Diego Jack Murphy Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
"I think for us to win, it has to be a fairly low-scoring game," Wagner said 
Tuesday in a conference call. 
</P>
<P>
"We're not going to win if the score is in the mid-30s or higher, I don't 
think." 
</P>
<P>
The Rainbow Warriors are ranked first in the WAC in total defense, allowing an 
average of 306 yards a game. 
</P>
<P>
SDSU, though, is ranked second in the WAC in total offense, averaging 490 yards 
a game. And on the heels of a 66-14 pounding of Utah, the Aztecs are feeling 
particularly confident this week. 
</P>
<P>
"Offensively, we might be close to Brigham Young or Houston, where the balance 
in our offense is difficult to defend," Luginbill said. "It doesn't matter who 
we're playing." SCOTT MILLER 
</P>
</TEXT>
