<HEADLINE>
<P>
EARNINGS; 
</P>
<P>
BRITISH STORE CHAIN PROFITS UP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
J. Sainsbury PLC, Britain's biggest supermarket chain, today reported its 
profits rose sharply in the first half of this year, boosted by eight new store 
openings in what was an otherwise weakening domestic economy. 
</P>
<P>
Pre-tax profit for the 28 weeks ending Sept. 29 jumped 27% to $538.6 million 
compared with $423.6 million in the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
Sales climbed to $8.43 billion from $7.33 billion. 
</P>
<P>
Sainsbury has built a leading market share with large-format stores supplying 
food staples as well as gourmet items. 
</P>
<P>
Sainsbury said its share of the British market rose to 12.1% from 11.3% despite 
strong competition. "Our exceptional price competitiveness has been fully 
maintained," company Chairman Lord Sainsbury said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
