<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHORT TAKES; 
</P>
<P>
BASS JAMES MORRIS RIDING HIGH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PHILADELPHIA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
American bass James Morris has been described as a bigger-than-life cowboy 
because of his love for wide open spaces and his imposing presence on and off 
the stage. 
</P>
<P>
He has also been described as demanding and aloof. 
</P>
<P>
But after a Monday night season opener for the Opera Company of Philadelphia, 
Morris was in good spirits -- partly because his wife performed in the same 
opera. 
</P>
<P>
Morris sang Count Almavivia ,the philanderer in Mozart's "The Marriage of 
Figaro." His wife, mezzo soprano Susan Quittmeyer, sang the role of Cherubino, 
a page and an unwitting foil for Figaro. 
</P>
<P>
Quittmeyer said the casting didn't happen by chance. 
</P>
<P>
"These are never coincidences," she said. 
</P>
<P>
Morris agreed, saying scheduling was a problem in their personal lives. 
</P>
<P>
"It's great when we get a chance to be in the same part of the country and even 
greater to be together in a production," he said. "I especially like it when we 
can both go to Santa Fe because I love the West, too." 
</P>
<P>
The couple lives in New Jersey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, James Morris 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
